\begin_layout Subsection*
Potential Improvements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An obvious improvement to the HPR-RGFM method presented would be to use
 a better Riemann solver than the iterative, linearised solver devised in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:An HPR Riemann Ghost Fluid Method"

\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 be the matrix of left eigenvectors of the primitive system.
 As noted previously, the solver relies upon the fact that each of the following
 relations holds along the characteristic to which it corresponds:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L\cdot\frac{d\boldsymbol{P}}{dt}=L\cdot\boldsymbol{S}\label{eq:along-characteristics}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The right hand side was set to zero in the approximation process, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{S}$
\end_inset

 can become arbitrarily stiff, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, although no issues were raised in this study, there may well be times
 at which the source terms cannot be neglected.
 It may be that some numerical method is required to integrate 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:along-characteristics"

\end_inset

 from the left and right interface boundary states to their respective star
 states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, a completely different approximate Riemann solver could be
 employed, such as the universal HLLEM solver of Dumbser et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2016"

\end_inset

.
 This path-conservative formulation of the HLLEM solver works for general
 non-conservative systems (such as the HPR model) and is simple to implement.
 It's based upon a new path-conservative HLL method (building on the original
 method of Harten, Lax, and van Leer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Harten1983"

\end_inset

) but is claimed to be able to represent linearly degenerate intermediate
 waves 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

with a minimum of smearing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by evaluating the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the intermediate characterist
ic fields (given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Eigenstructure of the HPR Model"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are iterative exact Riemann solvers for the equations of non-linear
 elasticity (to which the HPR model reduces as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, they will work for applications of the HPR model to solids problems
 (and perhaps to very viscous fluids problems too).
 Although these solvers are computationally expensive, they are only used
 once at each material interface point at each time step, and thus the added
 accuracy that they provide may be desirable.
 There are two ways to formulate the equations of non-linear elasticity:
 one in which the deformation tensor (the analogue of the inverse of the
 HPR model's distortion tensor) is evolved in time, and one in which its
 inverse (the analogue of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

) is evolved instead.
 Miller's exact solver 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Miller2004"

\end_inset

 uses the first formulation and the solver of Barton et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Barton2009"

\end_inset

 uses the second.
 The former can be used to evolve 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

, from which 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 can be calculated.
 Unfortunately, both solvers critically assume that the source terms of
 the system vanish, and so are unlikely to produce the correct boundary
 conditions for the HPR-RGFM when modeling relatively inviscid fluids.
 It should also be noted that they cannot be used for problems involving
 heat conduction across material interfaces, and they do not take the thermal
 conduction subsystem of the HPR model into account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a different EOS is used in order to model solids, the derivations of
 the primitive systems matrices of the HPR model (given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:Matrix Forms of the HPR Model"

\end_inset

) will have to be performed again for each EOS, and the form of the eigenvectors
 will change (along with the systems solved to obtain the linearised approximati
ons to the star states for use in the HPR-RGFM).
 Although this is tedious, it is a straightforward derivation to perform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Intermaterial Heat Conduction"

\end_inset

 it was noted that the HPR-RGFM produces aberrations in the heat flux around
 the material interface, when using the temperature fix described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:An HPR Riemann Ghost Fluid Method"

\end_inset

.
 Without using a better Riemann solver, a possible way to remedy this may
 be to specify the desired value of the heat flux in the star state, based
 on physical considerations, rather than obtaining it using the procedure
 detailed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:An HPR Riemann Ghost Fluid Method"

\end_inset

.
 For example, take two different materials in thermal contact, with lengths
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x_{1}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x_{2}$
\end_inset

 and temperatures 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

 at their respective ends.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the thermal conductivity of material 
